  "prompt": "America is divided into how many classes of people?",
  "response": "The concept of dividing America into specific \"classes of people\" is complex and can vary depending on the criteria used\u2014such as income, wealth, education, occupation, or social status. Sociologists and economists often describe **three main classes** in the United States, though some models include more nuanced divisions:\n\n1. **Upper Class**: This includes the wealthiest individuals, often with significant inherited wealth, high-paying executive or professional jobs, and substantial influence over economic and political systems.\n\n2. **Middle Class**: This is the broadest group, typically characterized by stable incomes, homeownership, and access to education. It\u2019s often subdivided into upper-middle class (professionals, managers) and lower-middle class (skilled workers, clerical staff).\n\n3. **Lower Class (or Working Class/Poor)**: This includes individuals with lower incomes, often working in manual labor, service jobs, or facing financial insecurity and limited access to resources.\n\nSome frameworks expand this to include additional layers, such as:\n\n- **Upper-Middle Class**: Highly educated professionals with high incomes but not among the wealthiest.\n- **Working Class**: Blue-collar workers or those in low-paying jobs without significant savings or assets.\n- **Underclass**: Those in persistent poverty, often facing systemic barriers to upward mobility.\n\nThe exact number of classes and their definitions can vary widely based on the context and criteria used.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
